12. 
<taxonomicName id="C926325A86E4D409100CC5ED003CA055" LSID="36164CCC-22FE-54B5-A800-19304F36AC76" authority="(Ricardo, 1920)" baseAuthorityName="Ricardo" baseAuthorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Neolophonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neolophonotus hirsutus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutus">Neolophonotus hirsutus (Ricardo, 1920)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="58120874EC4339D6710F91B407F6E3C8" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="6B27245E7A2E6A76AE20BCDFFF4AA51C" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F860915FB159AB0F1B553801F3965741" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
This species, reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation id="BC868DAB91D9C127FA56DE7C02649571" author="Londt, JGH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Natal Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 166" refId="B7" refString="Londt, JGH, 1988. Afrotropical Asilidae (Diptera) 15. The genus Neolophonotus Engel, 1925. Part 4. The comatus species - group (Asilinae: Asilini). Annals of the Natal Museum 29 (1): 1 - 166" title="Afrotropical Asilidae (Diptera) 15. The genus Neolophonotus Engel, 1925. Part 4. The comatus species - group (Asilinae: Asilini)." volume="29" year="1988">Londt (1988)</bibRefCitation>
, is currently a KwaZulu-Natal endemic, apparently limited largely to higher altitude areas of the province. Its nearest recorded locality to Jacana is the Umgeni Valley Nature Reserve (ca. 
<geoCoordinate id="60E722B625B82EE2278292924D0252EF" degrees="29" direction="south" minutes="28" orientation="latitude" precision="15" seconds="32" value="-29.475555">29°28'32&quot;S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="ED3F2012384FC148C615B7CE237B6164" degrees="30" direction="east" minutes="14" orientation="longitude" precision="15" seconds="21" value="30.239166">30°14'21&quot;E</geoCoordinate>
) on the outskirts of Howick.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5548DF0B24773594DE9F1A95A9CB0968" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Adults of this species were encountered in low to moderate numbers during the four spring weeks 36-39. All encountered individuals were found in the lower field, especially in areas that had recently been burned.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="83C5897B4C4A770F4E91B2EE7BEEBAFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
This small to medium-sized species was invariably found resting on the ground or on vegetation close to the ground. While two specimens were collected with 
<taxonomicName id="923579E80A665EFFE8D4BF56F1E73EC4" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="1925" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Neolophonotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
prey, others were swept from long grass with very few actually being sighted. The species appears to be largely confined to 
<bibRefCitation id="3FA82BC089CE9ED95A8E17E2A7D4CF74" author="Londt, JGH" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Natal Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" pagination="97 - 122" refId="B9" refString="Londt, JGH, 1994. Afrotropical Asilidae (Diptera) 26. Ethological observations, and a possible ecological classification based on habitats. Annals of the Natal Museum 35: 97 - 122" title="Afrotropical Asilidae (Diptera) 26. Ethological observations, and a possible ecological classification based on habitats." volume="35" year="1994">
<normalizedToken id="6193337A723416B1F4F2E9A818071852" originalValue="Londt’s">Londt's</normalizedToken>
(1994)
</bibRefCitation>
ecological category 1c (open ground).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
